abstract: Here’s what a conversation with him reveals.
snippet: Here’s what a conversation with him reveals.
lead_paragraph: Much of the speculation about the future of news focuses on the business model: How will we generate the revenues to pay the people who gather and disseminate the news? But the disruptive power of the Internet raises other profound questions about what journalism is becoming, about its essential character and values. This week’s column is a conversation — a (mostly) civil argument — between two very different views of how journalism fulfills its mission.

abstract: You may not be able to tell the difference while you’re driving, but Acura’s new 4-wheel steering system moves the front and rear wheels in concert to improve high-speed steering response.
snippet: You may not be able to tell the difference while you’re driving, but Acura’s new 4-wheel steering system moves the front and rear wheels in concert to improve high-speed steering response.
lead_paragraph: Automotive innovation over the years has given us seat belts, hybrid powertrains and – most importantly – cup holders. Steering? It has changed somewhat, but for more than 100 years most cars have done just fine with the front wheels handling that job.

abstract: Tom Herman, Ohio State’s co-offensive coordinator and quarterbacks coach, would prefer not to be known as the Mensa assistant, but it has trailed him.
snippet: Tom Herman, Ohio State’s co-offensive coordinator and quarterbacks coach, would prefer not to be known as the Mensa assistant, but it has trailed him.
lead_paragraph: The first name on Urban Meyer’s list of assistant candidates: Tom Herman, he of the documented high I.Q. Herman, now Ohio State’s co-offensive coordinator and quarterbacks coach, would prefer not to be known as the Mensa assistant, but he did list his membership in the group on his first résumé at his mother’s suggestion, between his team captaincy and all-conference accolades. He asked various universities to remove that from his biography, but it trailed him like a blinking neon sign: I’m smart. Really, really smart.

abstract: Stanley, who played 21 seasons and was noted for a lumbering skating style, won four Stanley Cups with Toronto in the 1960s, including the team’s last championship, in 1967.
snippet: Stanley, who played 21 seasons and was noted for a lumbering skating style, won four Stanley Cups with Toronto in the 1960s, including the team’s last championship, in 1967.
lead_paragraph: Allan Stanley, a Hall of Fame defenseman who helped the Toronto Maple Leafs win four Stanley Cups in the 1960s, died on Oct. 18 in Bobcaygeon, Ontario. He was 87.

headline_main: Ma’am, Your Burger Has Been Paid For
headline_print_headline: Ma’am, Your Burger Has Been Paid For

abstract: Some of this season’s films address adversity in solitude — “All Is Lost” at sea, “Gravity” in space — or under confinement (“Captain Phillips”).
snippet: Some of this season’s films address adversity in solitude — “All Is Lost” at sea, “Gravity” in space — or under confinement (“Captain Phillips”).
lead_paragraph: Having endured a summer of existential threats to the planet — zombie hordes, alien invaders, the usual stuff — moviegoers can now settle in for an autumn of more intimately scaled ordeals. Spectacles of collective apocalypse, the staple of the blockbuster economy, give way to individual stories of adversity and the struggle to survive in limited space. Superheroes step aside in favor of ordinary (albeit highly competent) people equipped with nerve, resourcefulness and impressive but not always reliable technology. Their archenemies are the laws of nature and political economy, abstract forces that take the form of lethal satellite debris, heavy weather and desperate pirates.

abstract: In “Ninety Percent of Everything,” the British writer Rose George catches a ride on a giant container ship.
snippet: In “Ninety Percent of Everything,” the British writer Rose George catches a ride on a giant container ship.
lead_paragraph: Rose George is a young British journalist who writes smart books about subjects we mostly prefer not to think about. Her last one, “The Big Necessity” (2008), about human waste and society, is among the best nonfiction books of the new millennium. Give the paperback edition to the person in your life who never puts down the toilet seat.
